{"dataset":"articles","provider":"pursuit","banner_url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/2BuruliUlcerPicBanner-Image-Nigel-Hallett,-News-Corp-Australia.-Used-with-Permission.webp","id":"111390","text":"<p>Understanding how infectious diseases spread is crucial for developing effective prevention and control strategies, especially for diseases transmitted by vectors. </p><p>When we say vector, we’re talking about an organism that carries a disease-causing agent from the environment or from an infected individual to a non-infected one.</p><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/varieties/64w.webp 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/varieties/160w.webp 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/varieties/375w.webp 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/varieties/768w.webp 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/varieties/960w.webp 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/varieties/1280w.webp 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/varieties/1440w.webp 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/varieties/1920w.webp 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0018/111393/2BuruliUlcerPicBanner-Image-Nigel-Hallett,-News-Corp-Australia.-Used-with-Permission.webp\" alt=\"A close-up of a Buruli ulcer scar\"   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Buruli ulcers start as a painless nodule under the skin that can develop into large sores. Picture: Nigel Hallett, News Corp Australia. Used with permission.</figcaption></figure></div><p>These kinds of infectious diseases are a unique challenge to scientists. They require targeted and sophisticated research approaches, because identifying the vector and determining the vector species can be difficult.</p><p>For decades, researchers have been trying to understand how <a href=\"https://www.health.vic.gov.au/infectious-diseases/beating-buruli-in-victoria\" target=\"_self\">Victorians are getting infected by </a><em><a href=\"https://www.health.vic.gov.au/infectious-diseases/beating-buruli-in-victoria\" target=\"_self\">Mycobacterium ulcerans</a></em>, the bacterium responsible for the flesh-eating <a href=\"https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/Buruli-ulcer\" target=\"_self\">Buruli ulcer</a>.</p><p>This disease begins as a painless nodule under the skin that can develop into large ulcers, causing severe tissue damage and long-term disability if not treated promptly.</p><p>Case numbers have been <a href=\"https://www.health.vic.gov.au/health-advisories/buruli-ulcer-is-spreading\" target=\"_self\">rising sharply</a> in recent years, from 135 in 2020 to 238 in late 2023, at the same time as infections have emerged in inner Melbourne suburbs. </p><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/73352/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Sciences &amp; Technology</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/the-breeding-trap-targeting-melbourne-s-growing-mozzie-problem?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>The breeding trap targeting Melbourne’s growing mozzie problem <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><p>The Buruli ulcer is a public health issue, so understanding the how and why of transmission gives us a better chance at tackling the problem.</p><h2>Mosquitoes are the key</h2><p>For a very long time, we didn’t know how <em>M. ulcerans </em>was spreading.</p><p>The National Health and Medical Research Council Partnership initiative <em><a href=\"https://www.health.vic.gov.au/infectious-diseases/beating-buruli-in-victoria\" target=\"_self\">Beating Buruli in Victoria</a></em><em>,</em> a collaborative partnership, has made significant progress in understanding that transmission process.</p><p>This collaboration includes the University of Melbourne, <a href=\"https://www.doherty.edu.au/\" target=\"_self\">Doherty Institute</a>, <a href=\"https://agriculture.vic.gov.au/\" target=\"_self\">Agriculture Victoria</a>, <a href=\"https://www.austin.org.au/\" target=\"_self\">Austin Health</a>, <a href=\"https://www.health.vic.gov.au/\" target=\"_self\">Victorian Department of Health</a>, <a href=\"https://www.barwonhealth.org.au/\" target=\"_self\">Barwon Health</a>, <a href=\"https://www.csiro.au/en/\" target=\"_self\">Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation</a> (CSIRO), and the <a href=\"https://www.mornpen.vic.gov.au/Home\" target=\"_self\">Mornington Peninsula Shire Council</a>.  </p><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/varieties/64w.webp 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/varieties/160w.webp 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/varieties/375w.webp 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/varieties/768w.webp 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/varieties/960w.webp 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/varieties/1280w.webp 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/varieties/1440w.webp 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/varieties/1920w.webp 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0019/111394/3BuruliUlcerMosuitoTeamPic-copy.webp\" alt=\"A group photo of some of the ’Beating Buruli in Victoria’ team\"   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Part of the Beating Buruli in Victoria team. Back row: Dr Peter Mee, Nicholas Bell, Prof Tim Stinear, Prof Paul Johnson and Jessica Porter. Front row: Dr Véronique Paris, Dr Kim Blasdell, Dr Ee Laine Tay, Dr Emma Hobbs, Dr Katherine Gibney and Dr Andrew Buultjens. Not pictured: Prof Ary Hoffmann, Dr Sara Windecker, Caroline Lavender, Maria Globan, Prof Nick Golding, Prof John Wallace, Dr Arvind Yerramilli, Dr Koen Vandelannoote and Dr Stacey Lynch-Allen. Picture: Rahul Ratwatte/Doherty Institute</figcaption></figure></div><p>Our <a href=\"https://www.doherty.edu.au/news-events/news/80-year-mystery-solved-mosquitoes-spread-flesh-eating-buruli-ulcer\" target=\"_self\">team’s research</a> has revealed strong evidence that mosquitoes are key in spreading the bacterium that causes the ulcer.</p><p>This finding is a crucial step toward developing targeted strategies to control the disease. </p><p>But it also raises new questions that must be addressed before this knowledge can effectively reduce the number of cases in humans.</p><p>Other areas of research are essential in the fight against the Buruli ulcer.</p><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0027/77535/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Sciences &amp; Technology</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/q-amp-a-victoria-s-monster-mosquito-explosion?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>Q&amp;A: Victoria’s monster mosquito explosion <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><p>Medical researchers are working on improved treatments and prevention strategies; wildlife researchers are studying the reservoirs of the bacterium; and microbiologists are examining the bacterium itself.</p><p>Our primary focus, as the <a href=\"https://blogs.unimelb.edu.au/pearg/\" target=\"_self\">mosquito team</a> from the University of Melbourne and <a href=\"https://agriculture.vic.gov.au/\" target=\"_self\">Agriculture Victoria</a>, is gaining a comprehensive understanding of local mosquito species.</p><h2>Understanding your local mozzies</h2><p>One of our main objectives is to find effective, sustainable and cost-efficient ways to reduce mosquito populations. Doing this will lower the risk of human infection.</p><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/varieties/64w.webp 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/varieties/160w.webp 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/varieties/375w.webp 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/varieties/768w.webp 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/varieties/960w.webp 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/varieties/1280w.webp 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/varieties/1440w.webp 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/varieties/1920w.webp 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0021/111396/5BuruliUlcerMosquitosBacteriaAlys-Young.webp\" alt=\"Véronique Paris identifying mosquito breeding sites in Melbourne’s suburbs\"   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Dr Véronique Paris identifying mosquito breeding sites in Melbourne’s suburbs. Picture: Alys Young</figcaption></figure></div><p>While this might seem straightforward, achieving it requires a deep understanding of the ecological and genetic traits of mosquito species.</p><p>For example, knowing how far a mosquito can travel helps determine the size of the area that needs control measures, as well as the duration these measures should be applied.</p><p>One of our recent <a href=\"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41437-022-00584-4\" target=\"_self\">studies</a> have shown that the local Australian backyard mosquito (<em><a href=\"https://wrbu.si.edu/vectorspecies/mosquitoes/notoscriptus\" target=\"_self\">Aedes notoscriptus</a></em>) from the Mornington Peninsula travel approximately 10 times further than the Dengue fever mosquito (<em><a href=\"https://research.csiro.au/mozzieproject/faqs/about-the-sit-method/\" target=\"_self\">Aedes aegypti</a></em>).</p><!--[--><!--noindex--><article class=\"ps-cta container\" data-component=\"CallToAction\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__flex\" data-v-1d83364b><div data-v-1d83364b><img src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0011/102233/varieties/375w.jpg\" data-v-1d83364b></div></div><div class=\"ps-cta__info\" data-v-1d83364b><div class=\"ps-cta__top\" data-v-1d83364b><p class=\"ps-cta__channel ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-text-uppercase\" data-v-1d83364b>Sciences &amp; Technology</p></div><a class=\"ps-cta__link ps-ff-source-sans-pro ps-fw-semibold ps-lh-120 ps-cta__black\" href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/5-slightly-disgusting-facts-about-mozzies?in_c=in_article_cta\" target=\"_self\" data-v-1d83364b><p data-v-1d83364b>5 slightly disgusting facts about mozzies <i class=\"ps-icon--arrow-right ps-cta__black\" data-v-1d83364b></i></p></a></div></article><!--endnoindex--><!--]--><p>Our <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/the-breeding-trap-targeting-melbourne-s-growing-mozzie-problem\" target=\"_self\">recent trial</a>, the design of which is based on these movement results, involves a new mosquito control station in Melbourne's Inner-West suburbs. </p><p>So far, it’s yielding promising results.</p><p>But our research goes beyond just reducing mosquito populations.</p><p>We also focus on understanding how mosquitoes interact with pathogens.</p><div class=\"container\" data-v-012796f8><figure class=\"ps-figure\" data-v-012796f8><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"ps-figure__image\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px\" srcset=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/varieties/64w.webp 64w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/varieties/160w.webp 160w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/varieties/375w.webp 375w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/varieties/768w.webp 768w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/varieties/960w.webp 960w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/varieties/1280w.webp 1280w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/varieties/1440w.webp 1440w,https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/varieties/1920w.webp 1920w\" src=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/__data/assets/image/0020/111395/4BuruliUlcerMosquitoPeterMeeSimonSchluter.webp\" alt=\"Dr Peter Mee setting up traps to collect mosquitos at the Mornington Peninsula. Picture: Simon Schluter\"   data-v-012796f8><figcaption class=\"ps-figure__caption\" data-v-012796f8>Dr Peter Mee setting up traps to collect mosquitos at the Mornington Peninsula. Picture: Simon Schluter</figcaption></figure></div><p>We’re exploring questions like: Where and how do mosquitoes acquire the pathogen? Is it from infected humans or wildlife, breeding or feeding sites, mating locations, or a combination of all of these?</p><p>By uncovering these details, we can improve our strategies and break the transmission cycle, with the ultimate aim of reducing the spread of diseases and improving Australia’s public health.</p><p>The efforts of the <em><a href=\"https://www.health.vic.gov.au/infectious-diseases/beating-buruli-in-victoria\" target=\"_self\">Beating Buruli in Victoria</a></em> team have earned recognition as finalists for the prestigious <a href=\"https://www.doherty.edu.au/news-events/news/beating-buruli-team-named-2024-australian-museum-eureka-prize-finalists\" target=\"_self\">Eureka Prize in Infectious Diseases Research</a>. </p><p>It’s work that exemplifies the value of scientific research and collaboration in solving real-world health problems. As the mosquito team, we are dedicated to continuing to advance mosquito control efforts and improve public health outcomes.</p>\n<p>This article was first published on <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\">Pursuit</a>. <a href=\"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/we-now-know-what-causes-the-buruli-ulcer,-but-what-are-we-doing-about-it\">Read the original article.</a></p>","date_published":"2024-08-09T13:43:29+10:00","date_updated":"2024-08-09T13:43:29+10:00","url":"https://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/we-now-know-what-causes-the-buruli-ulcer,-but-what-are-we-doing-about-it","title":"We now know what causes the Buruli ulcer, so what are we doing about it?","summary":"Knowing that mosquitoes are involved in the transmission of the Buruli ulcer in Victoria is a breakthrough, but we need to work out what happens next to tackle the disease","org_objects":[],"tag_objects":[],"author_objects":[{"name":"Dr V\\u00e9ronique Paris","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/veronique-paris","orcid":"","fae_url":"https://findanexpert.unimelb.edu.au/profile/813981-veronique-paris","email":""},{"name":"Dr Peter Mee","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/dr-peter-mee","orcid":"","fae_url":"","email":""},{"name":"Nicholas Bell","url":"https:\\/\\/pursuit.unimelb.edu.au\\/individuals\\/nicholas-bell","orcid":"","fae_url":"","email":""}],"citation_objects":[{"credentials":"Dr V\\u00e9ronique Paris"},{"credentials":"Dr Peter Mee"},{"credentials":"Nicholas Bell"}]}